The downside of this approach to work with the bills’ textual data is that we lose track of the weeks and the bills from which those texts where pulled from. This would make it very difficult to perform a time-to-event analysis of the disaggregated data about drowning occurrences extracted from the descriptions. In addition, the countings extracted from n-grams won’t make for a numerically accurate representation of drownings per week; they would only be of use to reveal interesting pieces of information about the drownings. 

*Building a data frame and a DTM*

The second approach is intended to retain the metadata from the Bills, particularly the date and week number. The goal is to build a new data set in which each row is a record, and the columns are the terms we tokenized from the whole corpus, that is, all the records present in the dataset. In this case, I transferred the text data into a Python dictionary after making a copy of the data frame and adding a new column called week_id. Python dictionaries are collections of key-value pairs that are unordered and mutable. In this dictionary the keys are the weeks, and the values are the text strings extracted from the `Drowned (Descriptive Text Column)`. 

