At this point, we have two options: we can transform the nested dictionary into a Document Term Matrix using again `CountVectorizer`from scikit-lear, or we can skip the DTM and go directly from the nested dictionary ‘tokens_dict’ to the data frame. The first approach retains the affordances of a DTM for text analysis, since it provides a more structured representation of text data that optimizes the computation of text analysis metrics and computations. This code line creates a document term matrix with each row representing a document and each column representing a term. The values in the matrix are the frequency of the corresponding term in the corresponding document.

```python
# Create a list of strings from the nested dictionary
list_of_strings = ["".join([f"{k} " * v for k, v in tokens_dict[doc].items()]) for doc in tokens_dict]

# Create the document-term matrix
vectorizer = CountVectorizer(lowercase=False)
dtm_dict = vectorizer.fit_transform(list_of_strings)
vocab = vectorizer.get_feature_names()

# Convert the dtm to a pandas dataframe
df_dtm_dict = pd.DataFrame(dtm_dict.toarray(), index=tokens_dict.keys(), columns=vocab)
dt_dtm_dict.head()

The downside is that it retokenizes the reconstructed Parishes causing that the nouns that we managed to rebuild are splitted again. Since we won’t be performing any sophisticated text analysis or NLP algorithms with the textual data, and we are mostly interested in counting how many times a parish is mentioned in the drowning’s texts, building a data frame from the dictionary and skipping the matrix appears the right way forward.

```python
#creating dataframe
df_drowned = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(tokens_dict, orient='index').fillna(0)
df_drowned.index.name = 'week_id'
```

After cleaning and double checking the spelling of parishes, this is what the data frame looks like. 

Finally, I left joined the new data frame with the original one to create a new master data frame. The master data frame preserves the metadata of each document (a record), but also serves as a document-term-matrix that includes all terms that appear in the collection of drowning descriptions withdrawn from the bill’s records. The values in this data frame are the frequencies of the terms in each of the corresponding terms. Note that most values are zero, because most words do not appear in most documents.

```python
df_drowned = pd.merge(lax, lax_counts, on='week_id', how='left')
df_drowned
```
