**Conclusion and Next Steps**

Text analysis provides useful techniques to dive into the lines of texts the Death by Numbers project is generating. Although for this blog I only worked with four years of data, we will eventually have textual descriptions from 1636 to 1754: that’s when text analysis will come in handy. By extracting the locations of not only drownings, but also suicides, killings and found dead, it will be possible to use GIS to build a spatial representation of these unfortunate events. By mixing the single token with the N-gram approach, we might also be able to provide context for those deadly occurrences. For the moment, we are only interested in what these texts are telling about drownings and sudden deaths in Early Modern London, and not in the patterns of the texts themselves. That does not mean that, in the future, and provided that we have a larger amount of text, we can focus on how the parish clerks wrote about dying in a water incident.
